Update Life Cycle Policy – User Guide (IBM COS)

Purpose

This form allows you to create or update a lifecycle rule on a bucket.

A lifecycle rule automatically deletes:

* current objects after a defined number of days
* or old versions of objects (if versioning is enabled)

⸻

⚠️ Important

When you use this form, you are modifying the automatic deletion behavior of the bucket, not just adding a simple setting.

Changes can impact a large number of objects.

⸻

Updating an Existing Rule

If you use the same rule name (Rule ID):

* The existing rule will be updated
* New values (days, prefix) will replace the previous ones

Impact

* Objects that matched the rule will now follow the new conditions
* This may result in:
    * earlier deletion of data
    * or longer retention

⸻

Creating a New Rule

If you use a new rule name:

* A new lifecycle rule will be created

Impact

* It may apply to:
    * the entire bucket (if no prefix is set)
    * or a subset of objects (if a prefix is defined)
* Multiple rules can exist at the same time

⸻

⚠️ Key Points to Watch

1. Deletion is permanent

* Deleted objects cannot be recovered
* There is no undo

⸻

2. Changing “Expiration days” affects future deletions

Example:

* Before: 30 days
* After: 5 days

Result:

* Many objects may quickly become eligible for deletion

⸻

3. Prefix defines the scope

* Empty prefix → applies to the entire bucket
* Defined prefix → applies only to matching objects

Be careful:

* Leaving the prefix empty unintentionally may affect all data

⸻

4. Versioning considerations

If versioning is enabled:

* Deleting current objects does not delete old versions
* Old versions may still consume storage

Use “Non current version expiration days” if needed

⸻

5. Changes are not immediate

* Updates are applied automatically in the background
* Deletion may happen with a delay (not instantly)

⸻

6. Existing rules may be affected

Depending on the configuration:

* Updating a rule may impact other existing rules

Recommendation:

* Always review existing lifecycle rules before updating

⸻

✅ Best Practices

* Use clear and descriptive rule names (e.g., logs-30d, tmp-cleanup)
* Double-check the prefix before applying changes
* Be cautious when reducing expiration days
* Review existing rules before updating
* Start with higher values if unsure

⸻

Examples

Safe update

Change from 30 → 60 days
→ Keeps data longer

⸻

Risky update

Change from 30 → 1 day
→ May delete large amounts of data quickly

⸻

Common mistake

Leaving prefix empty unintentionally
→ Rule applies to the entire bucket

⸻

Summary

This form controls automatic data deletion at scale.

Main risks:

* updating an existing rule changes behavior
* incorrect prefix affects the wrong data
* shorter durations lead to faster deletion

Always review your configuration carefully before applying changes.